Here is how much the 3 soccer balls weighed*:
Helium - 432 g
Air - 448 g
SF6 - 496 g
For the same force, the air-filled ball will travel at 98% the velocity of the He-filled ball; the SF6-filled ball will travel at 93% the velocity compared to He. A slower speed may result in less distance**.

*For those interested in the calculations:
Regulation soccer ball - circumference - 68-70 centimeters, weight 410-450 grams (use 430 gm in calculation).
Using 69 cm as the internal circumference of the sphere, R = C/2π = 11 cm.  V = 4/3*π r^3 = 5500 mL = 5.5 L.
Mass of gases - {V/(22.4 mol/L)*(Atm press + Gage press)/Atm press}*(molar mass of gas)
He - molar mass = 4.003; Weight = 1.8 g; Ball weight = 430 g + 2 g = 432 g
Air(dry) - molar mass = 39.948; Weight = 18 g; Ball weight = 430 g + 18 g = 448 g
SF6 - molar mass = 146.055; Weight = 66 g; Ball weight = 430 g + 66 g = 496 g
Ratio of initial(launch) velocities = (mass of lighter ball/mass of heavier ball)^1/2
Air compared to He = (432g/448g)^1/2 = 0.98 = 98%
SF6 compared to He = (432g/496g)^1/2 = 0.93 = 93%

**There will always be an optimal mass for a soccer ball to travel the farthest. That calculation depends on ambient wind speed (using calculus/differential equations).
